      <p>When buyers consider purchasing an apartment or townhouse in Brisbane's inner east, by-laws are increasingly part of their due diligence. Owner-occupiers want to know whether they can have a dog. Investors want to know whether they can list on Airbnb. Families want to understand the noise rules. Buyers who are serious about a property will read the by-laws before committing, and if they find restrictions they were not expecting, they will either negotiate harder, add conditions, or walk away entirely.</p>

      <p>Sellers who read the by-laws before listing, understand what they mean for likely buyer types, and communicate them clearly upfront are in a stronger position than sellers who leave buyers to discover restrictions during due diligence. Transparency early in the process builds trust. Surprises mid-campaign erode it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What are body corporate by-laws?</h2>
      <p>Body corporate by-laws are the rules that govern how lots and common property within a community titles scheme can be used. They cover everything from how you can use your balcony to whether you can keep a pet, where visitors can park, and what renovations require committee approval. By-laws are legally binding on all lot owners and occupants within the scheme.</p>

      <p>In Queensland, community titles schemes operate under one of several standard modules, each of which sets out a default set of by-laws. Many schemes then adopt scheme-specific by-laws that modify, add to, or override those defaults. These scheme-specific by-laws are where the meaningful variation lies. Two buildings on the same street in Newstead can have entirely different rules on pets, short-term letting, and noise hours depending on decisions made at general meetings over the years.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The by-laws buyers ask about most</h2>
      <p>In Brisbane's inner east apartment and townhouse market, several by-laws come up repeatedly in buyer enquiries and due diligence. These are the ones every seller should know before they put the property on the market.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Pets.</strong> Pet by-laws are among the most scrutinised by owner-occupiers. Many Brisbane inner east schemes allow pets subject to approval and conditions, but the specifics vary significantly. Some buildings restrict the number of pets per lot. Others restrict size or breed. Some require committee approval for each animal individually, while others allow pets as a standard condition. Owner-occupiers searching for an apartment who have a dog will ask about the pet by-law before they ask about almost anything else. If your building allows pets with reasonable conditions, that is a positive point to communicate clearly. If your building has restrictive or prohibitive pet rules, expect it to narrow your buyer pool.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Short-term rentals and Airbnb.</strong> This is the by-law that most directly affects investor buyer appetite. A number of Brisbane apartment schemes have passed by-laws that restrict or prohibit short-term letting through platforms like Airbnb, Stayz, and similar services. The motivation is usually amenity: owners who live in the building have concerns about the frequency of short-stay guests, security access, and noise. The legal position on short-term rental by-laws has evolved in Queensland following a 2020 ruling that confirmed schemes can validly restrict short-term letting.</p>

      <p>If your building has a by-law that restricts or bans short-term letting, that is material information for investor buyers, who may have been planning to list the property on Airbnb. Disclosing this upfront, rather than waiting for the buyer to discover it in the records search, is both the ethical and the practical approach. A buyer who discovers it late in due diligence will either renegotiate the price or walk away. A buyer who knows it upfront can make an informed decision and proceed with confidence.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Parking.</strong> Parking by-laws specify which spaces are allocated to which lots, whether visitor parking is available and how it can be used, and whether residents can use visitor bays for overnight parking. In densely developed inner east precincts, parking is a genuine constraint. Buyers with multiple vehicles or who expect to use visitor parking regularly will check the parking by-law carefully.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Renovations and alterations.</strong> Most schemes require committee approval for renovations that affect common property or the external appearance of a lot. What constitutes common property varies by scheme and is defined in the community management statement. Sellers who have completed renovations should be able to confirm whether body corporate approval was obtained for any works that required it. A buyer doing their due diligence will check.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Noise and quiet hours.</strong> Most schemes have by-laws specifying noise standards and quiet hours. These are typically less contested in sales campaigns, but they matter to buyers considering properties in buildings with a mix of owners and short-term tenants.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Where to find the by-laws for your scheme</h2>
      <p>The by-laws for your scheme are registered with the Queensland Body Corporate and Community Management (BCCM) office and are accessible via a body corporate records search. If you are not sure what the current by-laws say, the simplest approach is to contact the body corporate manager for your scheme and ask for a copy. They are required to provide this.</p>

      <p>The records search will also reveal any motions passed at recent general meetings that may have amended the by-laws, pending motions that could change the rules after settlement, and any disputes or adjudication orders that affect the scheme. Buyers will commission their own records search as part of due diligence. It is to your advantage to know what that search will reveal before the buyer reads it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers should do before listing</h2>
      <p>Read the by-laws for your scheme before you appoint an agent. Identify the provisions that are most likely to affect your buyer pool, particularly around pets and short-term rentals. If there are restrictions that will narrow the audience of buyers who can use the property as they intend, factor that into how you position the property and your price expectations.</p>

      <p>Your agent should be raising this with you at the listing appointment. An experienced agent who works regularly in the inner east apartment market will know which by-law provisions are most likely to generate buyer questions and will have a strategy for communicating them clearly during the campaign.</p>

      <p>Disclose proactively. Do not wait for buyers to find restrictive by-laws themselves mid-campaign. Proactive disclosure builds credibility, manages buyer expectations, and reduces the risk of late-campaign renegotiation or a deal that falls over because a buyer felt surprised by information they could have been told at the outset.</p>

